ODE XIII.

‘Bandusia Sabinensis agri regio est in qua Horatii ager suit? Aer. The Ode itself certainly suggests such a locality. The poet seems to be at home at the spring. The surrounding objeets are too familiar to obtrude themselves on the picture. The spring, now called‘ Fontana degli Oratini,’ on the hill-side between Vthe two suggested sites for Horace’s farm, answers well enough to the description. It gushes out suddenly at the bottom of a small sace of rock‚ crowned now, not by ilex, but by a fig-tree‚ and its rush of cold water. the crystal clearness of the basin which it forms, and then the life with which it starts to bound and prattle down the steep slope to the valley are quite enough to wake a poet’s enthusiasm.
